<DOC><DOCNO> AP891216-0143 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-89 2015EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     12-16 0281</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Philippines,0291</SECOND><HEAD>Communist Rebels Kill Mayor, Seven Others in Ambush</HEAD><DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Communist rebels killed a mayor andseven bodyguards in an ambush in northern Cagayan province, themilitary reported Saturday.   It said insurgents of the communist New People's Army arestepping up their attacks following the unsuccessful coup attemptby some military units earlier this month.   A military report said the ambush occurred Friday on a highwayabout 220 miles north of Manila and the rebels killed Tuao MayorRoberto Guimbuayan, four policeman and three civilan bodyguards. Itsaid the killers escaped.   Gen. Renato de Villa, the chief of staff, said the communistguerrillas were taking advantage of confusion within the armedforces since military mutineers launched assaults Dec. 1 trying tooverthrow the government of President Corazon Aquino.   He said communist guerrillas have made 17 attacks this month. Hegave no casualty figures, but other reports indicate at least 23people were killed in the guerrilla assaults.   At least 113 people were killed and more than 500 wounded inviolence related to the military revolt that collapsed Dec. 9 whenthe last mutineers gave up.   The armed forces said at least 3,000 military personnel tookpart in the coup attempt and more than half have been taken intocustody by loyal forces. The armed forces have about 160,000members.   Rumors persist of renegade troops trying to renew the uprising.   De Villa told reporters about 500 marines were airlifted Fridayto Davao City, 550 miles southeast of Manila, where there werereport of rebel troopers planning new attacks. But he added:   ``The coup is finished, and we are just making sure that thesituation does not deteriorate.''</TEXT></DOC>